&quot;Implicitly discarding information&quot; is just outright wrong.<p>All calls <i>can</i> have side effects, even calls that return a value. And while C# did recently add the discard operator _ to throw away returned values out of an e.g. Tuple, if you did as this critique suggests and flag every &quot;discarded information&quot; the language would become verbose&#x2F;obnoxious.<p>For example:<p><pre><code>      try 
      {   
            [....]
            myFirstDatabaseTransaction.Commit(); &#x2F;&#x2F; Compiler warning: &quot;Discarded Information&quot; (it returns the transaction ID, but has the side effect of committing your changes to the database).   
      } 
      catch([...])
      { [...] }

</code></pre>
Basic programmer errors are easily caught during development, because they&#x27;re immediately wrong. Unlike null reference exceptions which sometimes can only be found after extensive usage of the system (due to different states, or underlying data changing).
